      { question: "The RN observes continuous vigorous bubbling in the water seal chamber of a chest tube drainage system that was previously showing only gentle tidaling. What does this finding suggest?", options: ["Normal functioning of the chest tube", "An air leak in the system or from the patient's chest", "The need to add more water to the suction chamber", "The chest tube should be clamped immediately"], correct: 1, rationale: "Continuous vigorous bubbling in the water seal chamber indicates an air leak — either from the chest (persistent pneumothorax) or from a disconnection/crack in the system. The nurse should assess all connections, check for tube displacement, and notify the physician. Never clamp the tube to diagnose the leak." },
      { question: "Which action is essential for preventing central line-associated bloodstream infections (CLABSIs)?", options: ["Changing the central line every 72 hours", "Scrubbing the hub for 15 seconds with alcohol or chlorhexidine before every access", "Using non-sterile gloves for all central line care", "Applying povidone-iodine to the hub before access"], correct: 1, rationale: "Scrubbing the hub (needleless connector) for at least 15 seconds with 70% alcohol or chlorhexidine before every access is a cornerstone of the CLABSI prevention bundle. This reduces bacterial contamination at the most common entry point for infection. Central lines should not be routinely changed on a schedule." },
      { question: "A patient's arterial line waveform suddenly becomes flat (no waveform visible). What should the RN do FIRST?", options: ["Notify the physician for immediate line removal", "Assess the patient's clinical status and check the system for disconnection, kinks, or loss of pressure in the flush bag", "Increase the flush rate to restore the waveform", "Obtain a stat ABG from the arterial line"], correct: 1, rationale: "A flat arterial line waveform can be a technical problem (disconnection, empty flush bag, kinked tubing, clot) or represent a clinical emergency (cardiac arrest, severe hypotension). Assess the patient first, then systematically troubleshoot the system. A disconnected arterial line can cause rapid hemorrhage — check all connections." }
